<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-12-14T13:29:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-12-14T13:29:00-05:00" n="68" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d68">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">837.73/24: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Long</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Habana</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-12-14T13:00:00-05:29"><hi rend="italic">December 14,
                                        1920—1 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 8:46
                            p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>347. Department’s telegram no. 254. I am told by Dr. Patterson that he
                            has been informed by the Secretary of the Interior that without the
                            Habana-Florida cable the Western Union Company could not connect its
                            cable between Habana and Barbados according to the terms of the permits
                            it possesses at present. It was the opinion of the Secretary of the
                            Interior, however, that it would not be possible to prevent the Western
                            Union from relaying communications through its office in Habana.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Long</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
